node.text: Masculinity has nothing to do with beards and good looks and how you respond to criticism. It is all about your choice to stand up for what you believe in. This guy here was told to do get this singer off stage and instead comforted her in a moment which must’ve been absolutely heart-wrenching. Masculinity is about being there for other people, no matter superficial things like race and gender, and supporting them in their time of need. Another often forgotten part of it, but equally important, is letting others help you when you need support.
@joshuacfoy EXACTLY. My father is probably the strongest person I know, and he cries at insurance add because he’s not afraid to show his emotions

[Album: short story] #SineadOConnor once stood up for children who were being sexually abused and got backlash from big names like #AndrewDiceClay, #FrankSinatra, & #JonathanKing. Since the release of the #Gillettead Stories like this are being shared as examples of ideal standards of male behavior.  #beyondtheinterview #musicindustry #thepope #catholicchurch #toxicmasculinity #gillette #gilettead #childabuse
@road._to.__.nowhere @rafaelkg24

Feminists aren't personally accusing you of anything just exposing bull shit. Again I'm not the victim here. There are men and women who are exceedingly disadvantaged in society because of toxic masculinity.

@micayla_micayla_micayla Toxic Masculinity doesn’t pertain to *acts*, it talks about the shallow, surface ideals of “manliness” which puts pressure on men to act in a certain way (clothing, locker room talk, muscles, sports) to be considered to be a man, without allowing the deep inner work of what being masculine actually means to come through (moral fortitude, inner strength, wisdom, compassion, caregiving, etc). It’s when the farce of “manhood” overwhelms the good qualities of men and the bad acts you listed come out— symptoms of men not feeling adequate because of the pressure they put in each other. It’s a lot like how women experience toxic femininity when they berate each other as sluts or fat— we put the most pressure on each other to be superficially feminine instead of allowing the true feminine nature to surface. I’d love to see men concerned about that, but it’s rare to see a man that isn’t happy to hear a woman call another women a slut (thanks to toxic masculinity that teaches caring about women isn’t manly). If that makes more sense to you.

@micayla_micayla_micayla I think “toxic masculinity” is the wrong term. Instead, it’s almost more like a bastardization of masculinity, and how some (many?) in society have warped the meaning of masculinity to include horrible acts and disrespect toward women.

It was beautiful until the last slide. There is absolutely no science behind the “toxic masculinity” narrative. Many men are raised by single mothers, are around female teachers most of their childhood and become sexual assault perpetrators. Statistics show that  men who are raised with a masculine presence actually respect women. Masculinity is necessary for male child development. Being a narcissist is toxic. Being a rapist is toxic. Being a deranged sadistic person is toxic. None of these are directly related to masculinity.
@jessicakroche Yes, enablers of child abuse/sex trafficking do deserve far more respect than we give them, those poor, misunderstood pedophiles. 🎻
@jessicakroche more disrespectful to ignore and condone the global abuse of children by catholic priests. But sure. Ripping up a picture is far more damaging.
Absolutely disrespectful to rip a picture of the pope up though.. she knew it would cause controversy

Image may contain: 1 person, text that says 'Audra Williams @audrawilliams Ten days later, she was scheduled to perform at Madison Square Gardens, as part of a celebration of Bob Dylan. As soon as she got to the microphone, the audience began loudly booing her, seemingly in unison.'
Image may contain: 1 person, text that says 'Audra Williams @audrawilliams She talked later about how awful the sound was, and how she thought she was going to be sick.'

Image may contain: 1 person, text that says 'Audra Williams @audrawilliams The organizers tasked Kris Kristofferson with removing O'Connor from the stage. He instead went out and put his arm around her and checked in on her and stayed until she'd steadied herself and was ready to perform. When she came off stage, he wrapped her in a bear hug.'

Image may contain: 1 person, text that says 'Audra Williams @audrawilliams About the incident, he says: "Sinead had just recently on Saturday Night Live torn up a picture of the Pope, in a gesture that I thought was very misunderstood And she came out and got booed. They told me to go get her off the stage and I said 'I'm not about to do that' [...]'
